			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2011</a> paper:</span><br><i>Comparison of Context-Free Grammars Based on Parsing Generated Test Data</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/BerndFischer.html">Bernd Fischer</a>, <a href="../profile/RalfLämmel.html">Ralf Lämmel</a>, <a href="../profile/VadimZaytsev.html">Vadim Zaytsev</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-28830-2_18">10.1007/978-3-642-28830-2_18</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5c.html"><span class="tagM">T5C: Testing</span></a><ul><li> It proposes comparing grammars via automatically generated test data for parsers, i.e., a testing-based method.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> Grammar comparison is fundamentally an analysis task over language descriptions.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL">T5E: Empirical Evaluation</span></a><ul><li> The approach depends on empirical evidence obtained by parsing generated inputs and comparing outcomes.
</li></ul></li></ul>
